Data analysis

fse

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict fse with age, group and time_point (formula: fse ~ 1 + age + group + time_point + group * time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The models total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.72) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.18. The models intercept, corresponding to age = 0, group = control and time_point = 1st , is at 12.41 (S.E. = 2.73, p < .001, 95% CI [7.05, 17.77]). Within this model:

  • The effect of age is statistically significant and positive (beta = 0.11, S.E. = 0.05, p = 0.022, 95% CI [0.02, 0.20]; Std. beta = 0.38, 95% CI [0.06, 0.71])
  • The effect of group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.16, S.E. = 1.37, p = 0.907, 95% CI [-2.84, 2.52]; Std. beta = -0.04, 95% CI [-0.72, 0.64])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.79, S.E. = 0.85, p = 0.352, 95% CI [-2.45, 0.87]; Std. beta = -0.20, 95% CI [-0.62, 0.22])
  • The interaction effect of time point [2nd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and positive (beta = 4.04, S.E. = 1.24, p = 0.001, 95% CI [1.61, 6.47]; Std. beta = 1.03, 95% CI [0.41, 1.65])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.
